My pleasure.  A cube is a form that is composed of 6 sides of equal surface are in the shape of squares.  A square is a closed two-dimensional shape which is formed by 4 edges which have the same lengths, and have right angles in all four corners.  A sphere is a three dimensional form wherein every point on the outer surface of the sphere is equidistant from the physical center.  Therefore, no form that has non-zero dimensions can be both a cube and sphere.  Thus the non-existence of a cubic sphere has been proven.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My making of the assertion for non-existence cannot be proven aside form application of Ockham's Razor or the disproof of affirmative qualities she claims.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yeah, this exact topic came up in a religious debate between two of the professors at my university.  Technically the debate was upon the existence of a deity, but the reasoning behind the conclusion can be applied to a soul as well.  Both professors were philosophy professors, with relatively equivalent background in debating expertise.  They both tried as hard as they could to impress the reasoning behind their positions.  In the end, the atheist professor had to concede that the burden of proof for this topic rested on the atheist for one very good reason.  In this world there are millions, if not billions of different opinions of what god is.  Thus, it is more probable that at least one of them accurately describes an existing entity than for all of them to describe a non-existing entities.  Just as there are countless visages to the potential deities, there are countless visages applied to the potential human soul.  Some people feel it to be an ethereal body, some feel that is something that cannot be accurately described, others feel that it is a pattern of biochemical impulses that occur in the human brain.  That is why I find it so funny when I see atheists saying that there is proof that no deities exist by use of the omnipotence paradox.<br>
