<br>
Here is how the non-existence proof fallacy breaks down.  There are 4 basic postulates.  All A is B, all A is not B, some A is B, and some A is not B.  To disprove any one you need the obverse argument. For example, to disprove All A is B, you need only prove at least one thing in A is not B, or Some A is not B.  To claim there is one thing in existence that is A (for this discussion God, unless you prefer soul) you would have to roll it out and demonstrate it’s existence.  To disprove that, you would have to roll out EVERTHING IN EXISTENCE and show that ABSOLUTELY NONE OF THEM are a god.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In the end, the atheist professor had to concede that the burden of proof for this topic rested on the atheist for one very good reason. In this world there are millions, if not billions of different opinions of what god is. Thus, it is more probable that at least one of them accurately describes an existing entity than for all of them to describe a non-existing entities. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While this is another amusing twist for the debate, it falls short of the mark again.  The soul is a different thing from a god, but for the purposes of this I will follow the argument.  Your professors failed to agree on terms, and the failure to agree derailed the argument.  Because no one could agree on what a soul (or god) is, there is a insurmountable obstacle to debate.  If you define a soul as the electro-chemical impulses carried in our brains, the debate has one direction; if you define it as an etheric essence of divine origin, it has another (profoundly different I might add.)  Electric impulses can be measured, chemicals can be detected, proof can be obtained.  But is that just a revision of the definition of 'soul' into something that can be proven?  I could more supportably claim to worship the sun (as G. Carlin does) than a xian god because I can at least prove that the sun is there.  The 'more probable' reasoning is hugely flawed.  I can flip a quarter 1,000 times and get heads every time, the next flip it is neither more probable to get heads (and continue the pattern) than it would be to get tails (which is due for a turn) because they are not cumulative.  It will remain 50:50 - what poor reasoning these two professors of yours have.  Good thing they aren't teaching math!  The burden of proof, no matter what your professors want to take on for the world, remains with the one making the claim or positive assertion.  You claim a god, gaia, yahweh, vishnu, odin, ra, whatever, you claim it, then the burden of proof falls into your lap.  9 billion people can all claim a god, it is just plain lazy to assume 'one of them must be right' as your professors did.  Each claim is of a different and distinct thing (assuming they aren't all claiming the same thing) and each different and distinct thing must be proven on its own.<br>
<br>
I suspect that your professors were not really staging a debate in which they actually held opposing views.  It sounds more like they shared the same view and one took the opposite side so that they could hold a debate, but then did not try very hard to disprove his position.  The definition can be revised until you find one for god that fits reality, and you will end up worshiping the sun, or the earth or some other redacted nonsense, but the fact remains, of the major deistic religions, none of them prove god’s existence.  <br>
