Let me put it this way.  If given the choice between the existance or non existance of god, I choose to believe that he/she/it/they exist(s).  Am I certain god exists?  No.  As far as religious beliefs go, I am essentially an agnostic who has made the chioce to believe in deities for the time being.  <br>
<br>
One thing that I like about my belief system is that it is an ever-evolving belief system.  Unlike many people, when my belief system is challenged I don't turn a deaf ear to other people's thoughts and ideas.  If a part of my belief is challenged, I analyze the challenge, and if I find that I no longer am able to keep that part of the belief without abandoning reason, then I will edit/remove that part until it no longer contradicts reason.  In fact, ever since I ceased to be christian, I don't think that my beliefs have gone for an entire month without being edited in some way.  Officially I refer to my religion as wicca, as that is probably the closest religion to my own and it is the one whose ideals I like best; but it is unique, and as such it does not have a specific name. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=doublelatte>Double Latte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Got Milk?</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/19/03 10:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=214.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What do you call an atheist?</span><hr size=1> Well Phoenix, the key to flexibility is indecision.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
What I've found with being open minded about religion is that the more you cut away what's illogical or requires the abandonment of reason, the less you have left. Like you I'm an ex-Christian. When I finally threw out the bathwater I discovered there was no baby. I evolved from believing in Christ, to believing in an ill-defined but all-loving god, to believing in an amorphous and indifferent god, to not believing in god. <br>
<br>
I think you may be on the right path.<br>
